<subSubSection id="7FE273FBFA7E2ED9692329C92524071D" pageId="0" pageNumber="3" type="description">
<paragraph id="935FAC1FC3AB5691229AB625C995CC98" pageId="0" pageNumber="3">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1499E3B6198A108E47F376CFC82972F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="3">
Only one bunch of tubers are preserved on the specimen, tubers are ovate in shape, three tubers of equal size are arranged in one row (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F7DFC7B31048F5CAF6F7F67D9A3646FB" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. A-B Equisetum cf. pratense Ehrhart C-F Equisetum yenbaiense A. T. Aung, T. Su, T. V. Do &amp; Z. K. Zhou, sp. nov. Specimen numbers: A-B XTBGSZTF 0001 (counterparts) C XTBGVNMN 4002 D &amp; nbsp; XTBGVNMN 4001 E XTBGVNMN 4003 F XTBGVNMN 4004. n = node; r = ridge. Scale bars: 1 cm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.138.38674.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370028" pageId="0" pageNumber="3">2A-B</figureCitation>
). The length and width of the tubers are ~ 0.9 to 1.2 cm and 0.6 to 0.8 cm, respectively. Two to three longitudinal ridges are present on the surface of each tuber (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="83930195AB72FE17C80C41130AFA7747" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. A-B Equisetum cf. pratense Ehrhart C-F Equisetum yenbaiense A. T. Aung, T. Su, T. V. Do &amp; Z. K. Zhou, sp. nov. Specimen numbers: A-B XTBGSZTF 0001 (counterparts) C XTBGVNMN 4002 D &amp; nbsp; XTBGVNMN 4001 E XTBGVNMN 4003 F XTBGVNMN 4004. n = node; r = ridge. Scale bars: 1 cm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.138.38674.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370028" pageId="0" pageNumber="3">2A-B</figureCitation>
). The tip of the tuber is mucronate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A8AAFF09AA2A9F26DBB576ECA1731E08" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. A-B Equisetum cf. pratense Ehrhart C-F Equisetum yenbaiense A. T. Aung, T. Su, T. V. Do &amp; Z. K. Zhou, sp. nov. Specimen numbers: A-B XTBGSZTF 0001 (counterparts) C XTBGVNMN 4002 D &amp; nbsp; XTBGVNMN 4001 E XTBGVNMN 4003 F XTBGVNMN 4004. n = node; r = ridge. Scale bars: 1 cm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.138.38674.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/370028" pageId="0" pageNumber="3">2A-B</figureCitation>
). These characters fit well within the morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="E783A6659CFC930A4157AEC2261B1145" genus="E." lsidName="E. pratense" pageId="0" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="pratense">E. cf. pratense</taxonomicName>
, a fossil species reported from the early Oligocene in the 
<normalizedToken id="D6AA93D571B553F0AE94C151433E2A37" originalValue="LÃ¼he">Luehe</normalizedToken>
coal-mine, south-central Yunnan (
<bibRefCitation id="5C2E12EA30C5160C0D4E9CE8146E1379" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1086/510411" author="Zhang, YL" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Plant Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="3" pagination="351 - 359" refId="B42" refString="Zhang, YL, Ferguson, DK, Ablaev, AG, Wang, YF, Li, C-S, Xie, L, 2007. Equisetum cf. pratense (Equisetaceae) from the Miocene of Yunnan in Southwestern China and its paleoecological implications. International Journal of Plant Sciences 168 (3): 351 - 359, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1086/510411" title="Equisetum cf. pratense (Equisetaceae) from the Miocene of Yunnan in Southwestern China and its paleoecological implications." url="https://doi.org/10.1086/510411" volume="168" year="2007">Zhang et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="45C731A886F851F6229FD5864B8AECF1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1130/G39693.1" author="Linnemann, U" journalOrPublisher="Geology" pageId="0" pageNumber="3" pagination="3 - 6" refId="B23" refString="Linnemann, U, Su, T, Kunzmann, L, Spicer, RA, Ding, WN, Spicer, TEV, Zieger, J, Hofmann, M, Moraweck, K, Gaertner, A, Gerdes, A, Marko, L, Zhang, ST, Li, SF, Tang, H, Huang, J, Mulch, A, Mosbrugger, V, Zhou, ZK, 2018. New U-Pb dates show a Paleogene origin for the modern Asian biodiversity hot spots. Geology 46 (1): 3 - 6, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1130/G39693.1" title="New U-Pb dates show a Paleogene origin for the modern Asian biodiversity hot spots." url="https://doi.org/10.1130/G39693.1" volume="46" year="2018">Linnemann et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
